[{"id":"VR021695","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div>Which of the following statements best accounts for the fact that the peak on the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mstyle> <mrow> <mtext>He</mtext> </mrow> </mstyle> </math></span></span> spectrum is farther to the left and higher than the peak on the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"H\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> spectrum?</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR021695_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two photoelectron spectra, one labeled Hydrogen and the other labeled Helium. In each graph, the horizontal axis is labeled Energy, in megajoules per mole, and from left to right, the numbers 10 and 0 are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled Relative Number of Electrons, and no values are indicated. In the graph for Hydrogen, there is a peak roughly nine tenths of the way across the graph, close to 0 megajoules per mole. In the graph for Helium, there is a peak roughly eight tenths of the way across the graph, farther to the left then the peak for hydrogen. The helium peak is about twice the height of the hydrogen peak.\" height=\"472\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR021695.g01.png\" width=\"350\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The photoelectron spectra for <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"H\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mstyle> <mrow> <mtext>H</mtext> </mrow> </mstyle> </math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> are represented above.</p>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has an additional valence electron in a higher energy level than the valence electron in <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H\"><math alttext=\"H\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a greater nuclear charge than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H\"><math alttext=\"H\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and an additional electron in the same energy level.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> has a completely filled valence shell in which the electrons are a greater distance from the nucleus than the distance between the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H\"><math alttext=\"H\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> nucleus and its electron.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It takes longer for the electrons in <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> to be removed due to the higher nuclear mass of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e\"><math alttext=\"H e\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>He</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>"],"answer":1}]